{"pageProps":{"post":{"slug":"comments-in-bash","id":"66e02c5a4d1d260001ae643a","uuid":"9c8cf2ea-9f64-432c-a52a-947a92d66fce","title":"Comments in Bash","html":"<p></p><ol><li><strong>Single-Line Comments:</strong> Start with the <code>#</code> symbol.</li></ol><pre><code class=\"language-bash\">#!/bin/bash  \n# This is a single-line comment\necho \"Hello, World!\"\n</code></pre><ol start=\"2\"><li><strong>Multi-Line Comments:</strong> write multiline comments ****by enclosing the comments between&nbsp;<strong>&lt;&lt;COMMENT</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>COMMENT</strong>.</li></ol><pre><code class=\"language-bash\">#!/bin/bash  \n&lt;&lt; COMMENTS\nThis is a\nmulti-line comment\nCOMMENTS\n\necho \"Hello, World!\"\n</code></pre><ol start=\"3\"><li><strong>Inline Comments:</strong> Comments can be placed after a command on the same line.</li></ol><pre><code class=\"language-bash\">#!/bin/bash \necho \"Hello, World!\" # This prints a greeting</code></pre>","comment_id":"66c0704fd0323348cb7a522d","feature_image":null,"featured":false,"visibility":"public","created_at":"2024-08-17T09:41:35.000+00:00","updated_at":"2024-08-17T09:42:44.000+00:00","published_at":"2024-08-17T09:42:44.000+00:00","custom_excerpt":"How to do commenting in bash script","codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"url":"http://localhost:2368/comments-in-bash/","excerpt":"How to do commenting in bash script","reading_time":0,"access":true,"comments":false,"og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"email_subject":null,"frontmatter":null,"feature_image_alt":null,"feature_image_caption":null},"previous":{"id":"66e02c5a4d1d260001ae6438","uuid":"adc51e98-2008-4a95-be60-92737a1bd337","title":"How to Write Your First Bash Scripts?","slug":"how-to-write-your-first-bash-scripts","html":"<p></p><p><strong>Bash Script:</strong> Simple text file that stores a series of commands, typically entered in the command line, to automate tasks in the Linux system.</p><h3 id=\"how-to-write-bash-scripts\"><strong>How to Write Bash Scripts?</strong></h3><p>Ensure you're in the desired directory by using <code>pwd</code> command and if not then change to desired directory using <code>cd</code> command</p><ol><li><strong>Create file with .sh extension:</strong></li></ol><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.03.49-PM.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Screenshot 2024-08-08 at 5.30.00â€¯PM.png\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1104\" height=\"208\" srcset=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/size/w600/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.03.49-PM.png 600w, http://localhost:2368/content/images/size/w1000/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.03.49-PM.png 1000w, http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.03.49-PM.png 1104w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p>Execute the Script prefixing with <code>./file_name</code></p><ol start=\"2\"><li><strong>Open the script in text editor:</strong></li></ol><p><code>gedit apoo.sh</code></p><p>If gedit is not installed then run <code>brew install gedit</code></p><ol start=\"3\"><li><strong>Write down the bash script command within it:</strong></li></ol><p>ðŸ’¡ Every Bash script for Linux should start with the shebang line- \"#!/bin/bash\"</p><p>Letâ€™s start with the programming ritual- â€˜Hello Worldâ€™</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.29.03-PM.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Screenshot 2024-08-08 at 5.29.03â€¯PM.png\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"650\" height=\"130\" srcset=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/size/w600/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.29.03-PM.png 600w, http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.29.03-PM.png 650w\"></figure><p>If you excecute this file now, it will give permission denied.</p><ol start=\"4\"><li><strong>Provide execution permission and execute it:</strong></li></ol><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.30.00-PM.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Screenshot 2024-08-08 at 5.03.49â€¯PM.png\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"824\" height=\"140\" srcset=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/size/w600/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.30.00-PM.png 600w, http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-08-at-5.30.00-PM.png 824w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure>","comment_id":"66c06db5d0323348cb7a51f9","feature_image":null,"featured":false,"visibility":"public","created_at":"2024-08-17T09:30:29.000+00:00","updated_at":"2024-09-05T01:08:33.000+00:00","published_at":"2024-08-17T09:35:03.000+00:00","custom_excerpt":"How to create and excecute tour first bash script!!","codeinjection_head":"<script type=\"application/json\">\n  { \n  \"guide_name\":\"bash-guide\",\n  \"priority\": 1\n  }\n</script>","codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"tags":[{"id":"66e02c594d1d260001ae642a","name":"Bash","slug":"bash","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"canonical_url":null,"accent_color":null,"url":"http://localhost:2368/tag/bash/"},{"id":"66e02c594d1d260001ae642e","name":"#Import 2024-09-10 11:24","slug":"hash-import-2024-09-10-11-24","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"internal","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"canonical_url":null,"accent_color":null,"url":"http://localhost:2368/404/"}],"primary_tag":{"id":"66e02c594d1d260001ae642a","name":"Bash","slug":"bash","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"canonical_url":null,"accent_color":null,"url":"http://localhost:2368/tag/bash/"},"url":"http://localhost:2368/how-to-write-your-first-bash-scripts/","excerpt":"How to create and excecute tour first bash script!!","reading_time":1,"access":true,"comments":false,"og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"email_subject":null,"frontmatter":null,"feature_image_alt":null,"feature_image_caption":null},"next":{"id":"66e02c5a4d1d260001ae643b","uuid":"db84b81e-80f8-445e-9590-13b707acfe73","title":"Set Environment Variable in Linux","slug":"set-environment-variable-in-linux","html":"<p></p><p>Environment variables are dynamic values that the operating system and applications use to determine settings and configuration options.</p><p>These are used by applications launched in shells or sub-shells. These variables have a name and their respected value.</p><h3 id=\"setting-environment-variables-in-linux\">Setting Environment Variables in Linux</h3><p></p><ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Temporary Environment Variables:</strong> Set for the duration of the terminal session.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">VARIABLE_NAME=value\n</code></pre>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">MY_VAR=\"Hello\"\necho $MY_VAR  # Output: Hello\n</code></pre>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Permanent Environment Variables:</strong> Set permanently for all sessions.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Add the export command to profile files such as <code>.bashrc</code>, <code>.bash_profile</code>, or <code>/etc/profile</code> for system-wide settings.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Syntax:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">export VARIABLE_NAME=value\n</code></pre>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Example (add to <code>.bashrc</code>):</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">export MY_VAR=\"Hello\"\n</code></pre>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Viewing Environment Variables:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Use the <code>printenv</code> or <code>env</code> command to list environment variables.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Unsetting Environment Variables:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Remove an environment variable using the <code>unset</code> command.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">unset VARIABLE_NAME\n\n</code></pre>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Modifying Environment Variables:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Update the value of an existing environment variable.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Syntax:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">export VARIABLE_NAME=new_value\n\n</code></pre>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-bash\">export MY_VAR=\"NewValue\"\n\n</code></pre>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n","comment_id":"66c070acd0323348cb7a523b","feature_image":null,"featured":false,"visibility":"public","created_at":"2024-08-17T09:43:08.000+00:00","updated_at":"2024-08-17T09:48:14.000+00:00","published_at":"2024-08-17T09:48:14.000+00:00","custom_excerpt":null,"codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"tags":[{"id":"66e02c594d1d260001ae6427","name":"Linux","slug":"linux","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"canonical_url":null,"accent_color":null,"url":"http://localhost:2368/tag/linux/